Assess resutls with cross validation

# make prediction using the model on testing dataset 
glm2.prob = predict(model2_train, newdata = test, type = 'response')
# turn probabilities into classes (threshold = 0.50) 
glm2.prediction =ifelse(glm2.prob >= 0.5,1,0)
# assess performance 
# create confusion matrix
# right diagonal are the observations we got right, the off diagonal are the observations we did not ger right
conf_matrix2 = table(glm2.prediction, test$closed)
# show confusion matrix
conf_matrix2
               
glm2.prediction     0     1
              0 33744  4344
# percentage of observations assigned to the right class
acc_05 = (conf_matrix2[1]+conf_matrix2[4])/sum(conf_matrix2)
# percentage of observations assigned to the wrong class
miss_05 = 1-(conf_matrix2[1]+conf_matrix2[4])/sum(conf_matrix2)

It looks like the model predicts over 80% of observations however it is extremely bad at predicting company closure

2. Random Forest Algorithm

#install.packages("devtools")
#install.packages('randomForest')
library(devtools)
library(randomForest)
randomForest 4.6-14
Type rfNews() to see new features/changes/bug fixes.

Attaching package: randomForest

The following object is masked from package:dplyr:

    combine

The following object is masked from package:ggplot2:

    margin
# model random forest algorithm with 500 trees
forest = randomForest::randomForest(closed ~ nummortoutstanding + population +
                                    percentage_eco_active + percentage_unemployed_eco_active +
                                    percentage_ecoactive_level4_qual+ companies_in_the_city + uni_in_city,
                                    data=train,
                                    ntree=500,
                                    importance=TRUE)
#predict with random forest 
forest_prediction = predict(forest, newdata = test, type = 'response')
# create confusion matrix 
forest_matrix = table(forest_prediction, test$closed)
# show confusion matrix
forest_matrix
                 
forest_prediction     0     1
                0 33411  4168
                1   333   176
# percentage of observations assigned to the right class 
acc_forest = (forest_matrix[1]+forest_matrix[4])/sum(forest_matrix)
acc_forest
[1] 0.8818263
#  percentage of observations assigned to the wrong class
forest_miss = 1-(forest_matrix[1]+forest_matrix[4])/sum(forest_matrix)
forest_miss
[1] 0.1181737

Summary of performances

# create lists to then bind in dataset
accuracy = c(acc_05, acc_01,acc_015, acc_02, accuracy_small, acc_forest)
missclassification = c(miss_05, miss_01, miss_015, miss_02, miss_small, forest_miss)
models = c('Threshold = 0.5', 'Threshold = 0.10', 'Threshold = 0.15', 'Threshold = 0.20', 'Downsized Sample', 'Random Forest')
# create dataframe that compares all models and their ability to assign observations to the right class
comparison = data.frame('Models' = models, 'Accuracy' = accuracy, 'Misclassification' = missclassification)
# show dataset 
comparison
# create percentage of closed observations assigned to the right class
model05 = 0
model01 = conf_matrix_01[4]/38088
model015= conf_matrix_15[4]/38088
model02= conf_matrix_02[4]/38088
modelsmall = conf_matrixsmall[4]/38088
modelforest= forest_matrix[4]/38088
# create a dataframe comparing the models' ability to assign closed companies to the right class 
closure = c(model05,model01,model015,model02,modelsmall,modelforest)
comparison1 = data.frame('Models' = models, 'Prediction of closure'= closure)
# show dataframe 
comparison1

Visualise comparison of performance

#install.packages('ggrepel')
library(ggrepel)
comparison %>%
  na.omit %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Accuracy, Models, label= Models))+
  geom_point(aes(color=Models))+
  geom_label_repel()+
  # add writing
  labs(x = "% of observations (open/closed) assigned to the right class",
       y = "Models",
       colour = "Models",
       title = "Model with 0.10 threshold is the worst at classifying observations")+
  # change theme of the graph 
  theme_bw()

NA
comparison1 %>%
  na.omit %>% 
  ggplot(aes(Prediction.of.closure, Models, label= Models))+
